1
00:00:00,504 --> 00:00:04,284
Hello everyone and welcome
to CON42 LLMs 2026.

2
00:00:04,284 --> 00:00:08,284
My name is Petros Bazdaras, and today
we are going to confront a fundamental

3
00:00:08,284 --> 00:00:12,113
shift happening right under our noses
in the software engineering landscape.

4
00:00:12,854 --> 00:00:17,963
The title of my talk is Reading is the
New Writing: Why the AI Era Demands

5
00:00:17,994 --> 00:00:19,793
Absolute Mastery of the Basics.

6
00:00:20,323 --> 00:00:21,363
Let's dive straight in.

7
00:00:21,863 --> 00:00:26,703
We are living in an era where raw code
syntax has become an absolute commodity.

8
00:00:27,304 --> 00:00:29,593
What used to take hours now takes seconds.

9
00:00:30,003 --> 00:00:33,793
But make no mistake, the engineering
bar has not lowered, it has risen.

10
00:00:34,623 --> 00:00:36,303
Think about the workflow before AI.

11
00:00:36,604 --> 00:00:40,184
Developers spent hours writing
boilerplate, managing scaffolding,

12
00:00:40,193 --> 00:00:41,654
and repeating design patterns.

13
00:00:42,233 --> 00:00:44,903
Back then, output was a
decent proxy for skill.

14
00:00:45,373 --> 00:00:48,713
Now, it takes seconds to write a
prompt, and the LLM generates the code.

15
00:00:49,454 --> 00:00:52,343
But the real work begins exactly
when the model stops typing.

16
00:00:52,693 --> 00:00:55,833
Raw coding output is no longer
the metric of a software engineer.

17
00:00:56,333 --> 00:00:58,993
This paradigm shift has brought
a dangerous industry-wide

18
00:00:59,003 --> 00:01:02,733
threat, the black box, and a
massive delusion of productivity.

19
00:01:03,384 --> 00:01:07,083
We frequently mistake compiled
and working for good engineering.

20
00:01:07,803 --> 00:01:11,583
And let's be honest, shipping code
you didn't write and fully don't

21
00:01:11,613 --> 00:01:13,803
understand is a liability, not a win.

22
00:01:14,643 --> 00:01:16,513
This manifests in two major ways.

23
00:01:17,013 --> 00:01:22,383
First being cargo culting AI output,
accepting patterns that look completely

24
00:01:22,383 --> 00:01:27,533
right on the surface but embed subtle
anti-patterns, deep security gaps or

25
00:01:27,533 --> 00:01:29,364
highly inefficient logic underneath.

26
00:01:29,864 --> 00:01:32,314
Second, blind trust at scale.

27
00:01:32,704 --> 00:01:36,574
Every accepted suggestion blindly
compounds technical debt you didn't

28
00:01:36,574 --> 00:01:41,234
choose and may not even see until it
breaks in production As developers in

29
00:01:41,254 --> 00:01:46,854
2026, we now spend roughly ninety percent
of our time auditing, debugging, and

30
00:01:46,854 --> 00:01:48,644
maintaining what the model generated.

31
00:01:49,164 --> 00:01:52,954
Reading code has officially become
the primary engineering act.

32
00:01:53,754 --> 00:01:56,654
Right now, the industry is
split into two behaviors.

33
00:01:57,354 --> 00:01:59,044
First, we have skim and accept.

34
00:01:59,674 --> 00:02:03,364
The generated code looks correct at a
glance, so a developer clicks Merge.

35
00:02:03,624 --> 00:02:07,114
This is exactly how hidden
assumptions, edge cases, and so

36
00:02:07,114 --> 00:02:08,844
bugs slip straight into production.

37
00:02:09,494 --> 00:02:12,814
We have to move to the second
approach: read and verify.

38
00:02:13,194 --> 00:02:17,344
This means tracing the logic line by
line, actively testing the behavior,

39
00:02:17,683 --> 00:02:20,924
questioning the output, and deeply
understanding the trade-offs.

40
00:02:21,424 --> 00:02:24,074
Because the hard truth is
right there in the yellow box.

41
00:02:24,603 --> 00:02:28,064
If you can't understand the code deeply
enough to catch what the LLM missed,

42
00:02:28,634 --> 00:02:32,854
whether that's security flaws, performance
issues, or architectural misalignment,

43
00:02:33,523 --> 00:02:35,953
you cannot responsibly own the code base.

44
00:02:36,384 --> 00:02:40,634
The LLM writes, you must understand,
validate, and own every single line

45
00:02:40,634 --> 00:02:44,674
that ships This brings us to core
argument one, the autopsy problem.

46
00:02:45,304 --> 00:02:48,754
When the system inevitably fails
under heavy load, you're performing

47
00:02:48,754 --> 00:02:50,613
an autopsy on logic you didn't write.

48
00:02:51,294 --> 00:02:54,744
Relying blindly on probabilistic
code generation completely

49
00:02:54,754 --> 00:02:58,684
bypasses the developer's internal
mental mode of the system.

50
00:02:59,414 --> 00:03:02,814
Because you didn't actively
architect it, the intuition for

51
00:03:02,824 --> 00:03:04,594
debugging is entirely absent.

52
00:03:05,494 --> 00:03:07,734
These systems fail unexpectedly.

53
00:03:08,043 --> 00:03:11,414
Edge cases, race conditions,
and resource leaks only surface

54
00:03:11,414 --> 00:03:13,263
in production under real load.

55
00:03:13,763 --> 00:03:18,664
And remember, the on-call pager doesn't
care who or what wrote the code.

56
00:03:18,784 --> 00:03:20,764
The incident report has your name on it.

57
00:03:20,984 --> 00:03:22,054
You own the outcome.

58
00:03:22,554 --> 00:03:24,834
We must remember what LLMs actually are.

59
00:03:25,193 --> 00:03:26,904
They are pattern matchers, not engineers.

60
00:03:27,544 --> 00:03:31,314
They lack contextual empathy for
your system's long-term trajectory.

61
00:03:31,864 --> 00:03:36,654
Without a human guardrail, subtle security
vulnerabilities slip through undetected.

62
00:03:36,984 --> 00:03:42,813
Outdated library versions or depreciated
APIs are introduced, and algorithmically

63
00:03:43,024 --> 00:03:44,843
inefficient logic scales poorly.

64
00:03:45,543 --> 00:03:49,573
They have zero awareness of your specific
team's architectural constraints.

65
00:03:50,164 --> 00:03:53,693
This is why human intervention
is vital across three pillars:

66
00:03:54,174 --> 00:03:56,303
security, performance, and context.

67
00:03:56,833 --> 00:03:59,904
Foundational mastery is the
ultimate filter that catches

68
00:03:59,904 --> 00:04:01,543
exactly what the model misses.

69
00:04:02,043 --> 00:04:05,733
So how do we define the basics
in an AI-dominated world?

70
00:04:06,333 --> 00:04:08,483
It's not about memorizing syntax anymore.

71
00:04:09,103 --> 00:04:12,793
It's about the computer science bedrock
that lets you evaluate any code,

72
00:04:12,813 --> 00:04:15,213
regardless of who or what wrote it.

73
00:04:15,713 --> 00:04:18,153
This bedrock relies on three core pillars.

74
00:04:18,653 --> 00:04:22,533
First, data structures and
algorithmic complexity understanding,

75
00:04:23,203 --> 00:04:27,073
Otrade-offs, memory layout,
and why they matter at scale.

76
00:04:28,013 --> 00:04:32,543
Second, concurrency and memory
management, catching the race conditions,

77
00:04:32,643 --> 00:04:36,973
deadlocks, and garbage collection
issues that LLMs notoriously introduce.

78
00:04:37,803 --> 00:04:42,673
And third, system design and secure
coding, architectural reasoning, threat

79
00:04:42,683 --> 00:04:46,643
modeling, and the engineering principles
that outlast any trendy framework.

80
00:04:47,143 --> 00:04:51,183
Using AI to escape learning the
fundamentals doesn't make you faster.

81
00:04:51,683 --> 00:04:53,184
It makes you entirely dependent.

82
00:04:53,874 --> 00:04:55,693
Problem-solving is a cognitive muscle.

83
00:04:56,223 --> 00:04:58,213
Stop exercising it, and it weakens.

84
00:04:59,083 --> 00:05:00,243
Look at the fork in the road.

85
00:05:00,823 --> 00:05:05,634
On one hand, you have blind reliance,
skipping fundamentals, accepting

86
00:05:05,654 --> 00:05:10,714
all suggestions, and ending up
unable to debug generated code while

87
00:05:10,714 --> 00:05:12,474
accumulating massive technical debt.

88
00:05:12,974 --> 00:05:18,054
On the other, you have AI-assisted
mastery, applying CS fundamentals to

89
00:05:18,054 --> 00:05:23,854
order every output, catching errors early,
and building truly maintainable systems.

90
00:05:24,354 --> 00:05:28,634
The real risk of blind reliance
is a severely weakened debugging

91
00:05:28,644 --> 00:05:33,844
intuition, an inability to reason
about unfamiliar code, and a growing

92
00:05:33,844 --> 00:05:35,654
critical dependency on the tool.

93
00:05:36,154 --> 00:05:39,364
The career path for software
engineering has fundamentally shifted.

94
00:05:39,624 --> 00:05:42,354
We are moving from code
typists to system reviewers.

95
00:05:42,944 --> 00:05:46,694
AI amplifies leverage, but only
for those who already know how

96
00:05:46,694 --> 00:05:48,054
to code exceptionally well.

97
00:05:48,814 --> 00:05:51,864
Our role now mirrors that
of a managing editor.

98
00:05:52,564 --> 00:05:57,164
We must order every line the model
produces with a critical informed eye.

99
00:05:57,614 --> 00:06:01,474
We must secure systems by applying
the security fundamentals the

100
00:06:01,484 --> 00:06:03,314
model doesn't inherently possess.

101
00:06:03,954 --> 00:06:07,544
And we must scale architectures
that hold up under real-world load

102
00:06:07,894 --> 00:06:09,714
because we understand why they work.

103
00:06:10,194 --> 00:06:13,034
AI does not replace the
need to know fundamentals.

104
00:06:13,794 --> 00:06:16,773
It makes knowing them your
primary differentiator.

105
00:06:17,614 --> 00:06:20,774
To close things out, I want to leave
you with this final call to action.

106
00:06:21,404 --> 00:06:23,344
Don't just use AI to write faster.

107
00:06:23,834 --> 00:06:26,703
Use your mastery to audit,
secure, and scale better.

108
00:06:27,374 --> 00:06:31,184
Reading code is officially the
highest leverage skill in the AI era.

109
00:06:31,563 --> 00:06:32,204
Master it.

110
00:06:32,704 --> 00:06:34,184
Thank you so much for your time.

111
00:06:34,444 --> 00:06:35,794
Let's connect on LinkedIn.

112
00:06:36,154 --> 00:06:39,284
My name is Patches Bazdres,
and enjoy the rest of Conf

113
00:06:39,294 --> 00:06:41,364
forty-two LLMs twenty twenty-six.

